===Etymology===
From mid nineteenth-century {{etyl|de}} {{term|lang=de|Akkordion}} based on {{etyl|it}} {{term|lang=it|accordare||to tune}}. See also [[accord]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈkɔ(ɹ).di.ˌən/}}
* {{audio|en-us-accordion.ogg|Audio (US)}}`
* {{hyphenation|ac|cord|i|on}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A small, portable, keyed [[wind instrument]], whose [[tone]]s are generated by play of the wind from a squeezed [[bellows]] upon free metallic [[reed]]s.
#* '''1869''', [[w:Mark Twain|Mark Twain]], ''Innocents Abroad'':
#*: ''A disreputable '''accordion''' that had a leak somewhere and breathed louder than it squawked.''
#* [[w:Ambrose Bierce|Ambrose Bierce]], ''Devil’s Dictionary'':
#*: '''Accordion''': an instrument in harmony with the sentiments of an assassin.

